<!-- ABOUT -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>About Chemical Hazards</h2>
  <p>
    Chemical hazards occur when toxic gases, liquids, or solids are released into the environment.
    They can happen in laboratories, factories, chemical plants, warehouses, tanker accidents,
    or storage facilities.
  </p>
  <p>
    Exposure can irritate skin, eyes, lungs, or cause severe health issues depending on the chemical type.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- COMMON SOURCES -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Sources of Chemical Hazards</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Laboratories (acids, alkalis, solvents)</li>
    <li>Factories/chemical plants</li>
    <li>Gas leaks (e.g., ammonia, chlorine)</li>
    <li>Oil refineries</li>
    <li>Chemical storage tanks</li>
    <li>Transport tankers/spillage</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- WARNING SIGNS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Warning Signs</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Strong or unusual smells.</li>
    <li>Burning sensation in eyes or throat.</li>
    <li>Sudden coughing or breathlessness.</li>
    <li>Dead insects or vegetation nearby.</li>
    <li>Leakage or chemical stains around containers.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- SYMPTOMS OF EXPOSURE -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Symptoms of Chemical Exposure</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Difficulty breathing</li>
    <li>Irritated or burning eyes</li>
    <li>Dizziness, nausea, headache</li>
    <li>Skin burns or rashes</li>
    <li>Strong chest pain (severe cases)</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- PREPAREDNESS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Preparedness Steps</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Know emergency exits and assembly points.</li>
    <li>Wear lab coats, gloves, masks during practicals.</li>
    <li>Label all chemicals clearly.</li>
    <li>Store acids, bases, and flammables separately.</li>
    <li>Install exhaust fans and chemical hoods.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- DO‚Äôs & DON'Ts -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Do‚Äôs & Don‚Äôts</h2>

  <h3>‚úî Do‚Äôs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Move away from the chemical source immediately.</li>
    <li>Cover nose and mouth with a wet cloth or mask.</li>
    <li>Use eyewash station for eye exposure.</li>
    <li>Wash skin with plenty of water.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>‚ùå Don‚Äôts</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Do NOT touch spilled chemicals directly.</li>
    <li>Do NOT smell unknown chemicals.</li>
    <li>Do NOT run ‚Äî walk quickly but calmly.</li>
    <li>Do NOT use water on chemical fires (like oil or electrical fires).</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- HELPING OTHERS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>How to Help Others</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Help move people to fresh air.</li>
    <li>Wash exposed areas with clean water.</li>
    <li>Keep victims warm and calm.</li>
    <li>Report the incident to authorities immediately.</li>
    <li>Provide first aid until medical help arrives.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

